      "writtenOn": "2017-08-03T21:19:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "without a comment these two parameters aren\u0027t self-explaining.\nI\u0027d expect filelock to call some system wait until file becomes unlocked, so there\u0027s no tries. so |timeout| is ok. but |tries| suggest there\u0027s some loop - in that case |timeout| could be either for a single try or for the whole operation.\n\nBtw, when you\u0027ve detected the pid of the process that\u0027s holding a lock, in Windows you have an API to wait for that process without a sleep loop:\n\n    HANDLE process \u003d OpenProcess(SYNCHRONIZE, FALSE, pid);\n    DWORD ret \u003d WaitForSingleObject(process, \u003ctimeout_ms\u003e);\n    CloseHandle(process);\n\nMac has something similar, but more complicated via kqueue with EVFILT_PROC+NOTE_EXIT. And on Linux there\u0027s no simple API, it\u0027s either polling or http://bewareofgeek.livejournal.com/2945.html",
